AGI -&nbsp;&nbsp; The National Election Office at the Court of&nbsp;Cassazione&nbsp; accepts the appeal of Stefano Bandecch>i's Popular Alternative and admits the list to participate in the European elections. Ap had appealed against the decision of the Court of Appeal of Rome to exclude the list from the centre constituency. The Court of Appeal of Naples had admitted the list of Ap.
&nbsp;
"The Popular Alternative List - writes the National Election Office at the Court of &nbsp;Cassazione&nbsp;- meets the requirement of the certified affiliation to a European political party >constituted in a parliamentary group in the European Parliament in the current legislature at the time of convocation of electoral committees and must be admitted to participation in the election of the members of the European Parliament to Italy". Ap is affiliated to the Ppe and has the name 'Ppe' in its symbol >.
&nbsp;
The National Election Office at the 'Palazzaccio', considered the last bill converted by the Chambers, thus motivates its decision explaining that there are "two distinct hermeneutic options, both plausible: the one which imposes two requirements for the exemption (place already obtained to the European Parliament and affiliate certified to a group established there); the other that, in accordance with the previous text of the same fourth paragraph of Article 12, and with the relative interpretative tradition formatted from the preceding this Office of 2014, alternatively sets two requirements.
&nbsp;
The Office considers that the second hermeneutics option is prevalenced, > considering it more conforms to both constitutional principles in this field, as sums (though for other purposes) from the Note of Decision No 1 of 2014 of the Constitutional Court, and to Recommendation (EU) 2023/2829>, which recitals 10 as follows: The stability of electoral law is fundamental to the integrity and credibility of electoral processes. Frequent amendments to the rules or amendments which intervene immediately before the elections > may confuse voters and voters and may lead to distortions or misapplications of the rules. Such changes may also be perceived as an instrument intended to influence the results for the government already established. In accordance with the Guideline II.2.b of the Code of Good Election (6) published by the European Commission for Democracy through the right of the Council of Europe (the "Commission of Venice"), the fundamental elements of national electoral law should not be able to be modified less than a year before the elections. These fundamental elements include in particular the rules relating to the transformation of votes into seats, membership of electoral committees or other bodies organizing the vote, as well as the definition of the boundaries of electoral constituencies and the distribution of seats between constituencies. Although it is not appropriate to invoke the principle of the establishment of the electoral law in order to maintain a situation contrary to international electoral rules, nothing in this recommendation should be understood as an invitation to the Member States to take measures contrary to the Guideline II.2.b of the said Code of Good Election".
&nbsp;
It is unlikely, in fact, that "the legislator, in the gradient of the term of 180 days for the collection of signatures, and moreover only in the conversion of the Legislative Decree no. 7 of 2024, has intended to deliberately operate an overturn of the pre-existing rules in the matter of exemption from the sub-scriptions, > configuring the political parties only the Italian affiliation

